    <h2>Summary and Justification</h2>
    <p>This website was developed to offer a comprehensive, firsthand perspective on what life is truly like within a Division I football program. As a Health and Exercise Science student at Syracuse University who has interned with the football strength and conditioning staff, I’ve seen the behind-the-scenes efforts that drive elite athletic performance. This project merges academic research, practical experience, and real-world communication methods to highlight the often-overlooked factors that contribute to success at the highest levels of collegiate sport.</p>

    <p>The site is designed for multiple audiences—students considering careers in sports performance, strength and conditioning interns, aspiring collegiate athletes, and anyone interested in how elite football programs operate beyond the field. Each section breaks down a critical element of program life, from nonverbal communication to data analysis and education strategies used by coaches and support staff.</p>

    <p>One of the main reasons for building this site is the lack of accessible, realistic educational content about what it's like to work in or support a Division I team. Most content online focuses solely on athletes, leaving out the valuable perspectives of strength staff, analysts, trainers, and student assistants. This platform helps bridge that gap, offering valuable information on how to reach out to coaches, what to expect in different support roles, and how performance is tracked and improved across various metrics.</p>

    <p>Ultimately, this project serves not just as an educational tool, but as a professional portfolio piece that reflects my understanding of performance environments, coaching culture, communication strategy, and the impact of continued education. It’s my way of contributing to the field I’m passionate about while helping others prepare to join it.</p>

    <p>Based on insights from Syracuse Football Coaches and scholarly research (Gallo & De Marco, 2008; Pullo, 1989; Nelson, 2017; Winkler, 2013; NCAA Sport Science Institute Reports, 2023; NSCA Performance Benchmarks, 2022)</p>
